Aleksei Shokhirev / portfolio project 3¶

In this project we will analyze the marketing campaign for the online subscription business. Firstly, we will compute the common metrics such as conversion rate and retention rate. We will measure how the campaign performed for different marketing channels and across demographics. Secondly, we will check the accuracy of campaign performance and detecting bugs and their influence on the result. On the top of that, we will analyze A/B test and compute common metrics such as lift and t-statistics.

The marketing dataset contains following data:

  • 'date_served' - date the marketing assets have been displayed;
  • 'marketing_channel' - the type of marketing assets;
  • 'converted' - True if the customer subscribed False otherwise;
  • 'language_displayed' - the actual language of marketing assets;
  • 'language_preferred' - the language of customer preference
  • 'age_group' - the customer age group
  • 'is_retained' - True if the customer keep using a product after free trail finished and False otherwise
  • 'variant' - the A/B test result. Personalization means the customer received a personalized message. Control means generic upsells to the product.

# create functions
def users_by_metrics(df, columns):
    """Nuber of users across different metrics"""
    number_of_users = df.groupby(columns)['user_id'].nunique().unstack(level=1)
    return number_of_users

def plot_ads(axes, df, kind, title, ylabel):
    """Function for plotting retention and conversion rates"""
    df.plot(ax=axes, kind=kind, title=title, ylabel=ylabel, xlabel='')

def conversion_rate(df, columns):
    """Conversion rate function"""
    total = df.groupby(columns)['user_id'].nunique()
    converted = df[df['converted']==True].groupby(columns)['user_id'].nunique()
    conversion_rate = converted / total
    conversion_rate = conversion_rate.fillna(0)
    return conversion_rate

def retention_rate(df, columns):
    """Retention rate function"""
    converted = df[df['converted']==True].groupby(columns)['user_id'].nunique()
    retained = df[df['is_retained']==True].groupby(columns)['user_id'].nunique()
    retention_rate = retained / converted
    retention_rate = retention_rate.fillna(0)
    return retention_rate

def plot_metric(axes, df, kind):
    """Function for plotting retention and conversion rates"""
    df.plot(ax=axes, kind=kind, title=df.name, xlabel='')
    
def plot_metrics_time(df1, df2):
    """Function to plot metrics over time"""
    for c in df1.columns.values:
        plt.figure(figsize=[10, 4])
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
        plt.plot(df1.index, df1[c])
        plt.title(df1.name + ' by '+ c)
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
        plt.plot(df2.index, df2[c])
        plt.title(df2.name + ' by ' + c)
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.show()

def count_pmf_plot(df):
    """Count and Pmf plots"""
    for c in df.columns.values:
        pmf = Pmf.from_seq(df[c], normalize=True)
        
        plt.figure(figsize=[12, 4])
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
        sns.countplot(data=df, x=c)
        plt.title(c)
        plt.ylabel('Number of users')
        plt.xlabel('')
        plt.xticks(rotation=30)
        
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
        pmf.bar()
        plt.title('PMF ' + c)
        plt.ylabel('Fraction of users')
        plt.xlabel('')
        plt.xticks(rotation=30)
        plt.show()
        
def lift(control, personalization):
    """Function to compute the lift"""
    control_mean = np.mean(control)
    personalization_mean = np.mean(personalization)
    lift = (personalization_mean - control_mean)/control_mean
    return str(round(lift*100, 2)) + '%'

def ab_segmentation(channel, segment):
    """Lift and t-statistics across segments"""
    # iterate through each subsegment in marketing
    for subsegment in np.unique(marketing[segment].values):
        # limit marketing to email and subsegment
        df_channel = marketing[(marketing['marketing_channel']==channel)&(marketing[segment]==subsegment)]
        # ensure each user and variant has only one subscription outcome
        subscribers = df_channel.groupby(['user_id', 'variant'])['converted'].max().unstack(level=1)
        # isolate control and personalization
        control = subscribers['control'].dropna()
        personalization = subscribers['personalization'].dropna()
        # print conversion rate and statistical significance for each subsegment
        print(subsegment)
        print('lift: ', lift(control, personalization))
        print('t-statistics: ', ttest_ind(control, personalization), '\n')   

def conversion_ab_test(channel):
    """Conversion rate for control and personalization across marketing channels"""
    # first, we ensure each user and variant has only one subscription outcome
    subscribers_df = marketing[marketing['marketing_channel']==channel].groupby(
    ['user_id', 'variant'])['converted'].max().unstack(level=1)
    # isolate subscription outcome for control and personalization groups
    control = subscribers_df['control'].dropna()
    personalization =subscribers_df['personalization'].dropna()
    # compute the conversion rate for both personalization and control
    control_rate = round(np.mean(control), 4)
    personalization_rate = round(np.mean(personalization), 4)
    return control_rate, personalization_rate

def conversion_ab_test_age(age):
    """Conversion rate for control and personalization across age groups"""
    # first, we ensure each user and variant has only one subscription outcome
    subscribers_df = marketing[marketing['age_group']==age].groupby(
    ['user_id', 'variant'])['converted'].max().unstack(level=1)
    # isolate subscription outcome for control and personalization groups
    control = subscribers_df['control'].dropna()
    personalization =subscribers_df['personalization'].dropna()
    # compute the conversion rate for both personalization and control
    control_rate = round(np.mean(control), 4)
    personalization_rate = round(np.mean(personalization), 4)
    return control_rate, personalization_rate

def allocation(channel):
    """Allocation control and personalization across marketing channels"""
    allocation = marketing[marketing['marketing_channel']==channel].groupby('variant')['user_id'].nunique()
    return allocation

def control_personalization(channel):
    """Extract control and personalization across marketing channels"""
    # first, we ensure each user and variant has only one subscription outcome
    subscribers = marketing[marketing['marketing_channel']==channel].groupby(
        ['user_id', 'variant'])['converted'].max().unstack(level=1)
    # isolate subscription outcome for control and personalization groups
    control = subscribers['control'].dropna()
    personalization =subscribers['personalization'].dropna()
    return control, personalization

def control_personalization_age(age):
    """Extract control and personalization across age groups"""
    # first, we ensure each user and variant has only one subscription outcome
    subscribers = marketing[marketing['age_group']==age].groupby(
        ['user_id', 'variant'])['converted'].max().unstack(level=1)
    # isolate subscription outcome for control and personalization groups
    control = subscribers['control'].dropna()
    personalization =subscribers['personalization'].dropna()
    return control, personalization

def conversion_ab_channels(channel):
    """Conversion rates for control and personalization, lift and t-statistics across channels"""
    control_rate, personalization_rate = conversion_ab_test(channel)
    control, personalization = control_personalization(channel)
    print(channel)
    print('Control conversion rate:', control_rate)
    print('Personalization conversion rate:', personalization_rate)
    print('lift: ', lift(control, personalization))
    print(ttest_ind(control, personalization), '\n\n')
    
def conversion_ab_age(age):
    """Conversion rates for control and personalization, lift and t-statistics across age groups"""
    control_rate, personalization_rate = conversion_ab_test_age(age)
    control, personalization = control_personalization_age(age)
    print(age)
    print('Control conversion rate:', control_rate)
    print('Personalization conversion rate:', personalization_rate)
    print('lift: ', lift(control, personalization))
    print(ttest_ind(control, personalization), '\n\n')

Conversion and retention rates¶

Conversion rate is the percentage of users who saw the marketing assets and subsequently become subscribers. Conversion rate is one of the best ways to determine how effective a marketing team was at gaining new customers. Retention rate is the number of remaining subscribers from the users who converted to the company product. Retention rate can give a sense of whether the marketing campaign converted subscribers who are actually interested in the product. We will compute overall conversion and retention rates as well as conversion and retention rates across demographics and marketing channels.

In [17]:

subscribers_retention = marketing[marketing['is_retained']==True]['user_id'].nunique()
retention_overall = subscribers_retention / total_retention

# print the results
print('Overall conversion rate:', round(conversion_overall*100, 2), '%')
print('Overall retention rate:', round(retention_overall*100, 2), '%')

Those indices reflect the relative relationship of how well the marketing assets typically convert users for each language compared to English. As we can see, Spanish speaking users typically convert at 1.71 times the rate of English speakers. Arabic and German speakers convert at about 4.73 and 4.21 times the rate of English speakers respectively. Now, that we have created indices for each language compared to English, we can assess what the conversion rate should have been during the rest of the month. To understand the true impact of the bug, it is crucial to determine how many subscribers we would have expected if no language error occurred.

A/B test analysis¶

The marketing campaign was run as A/B test. Around half of the marketing messages were generic upsells to the product while the other half contained personalized messaging around the users` behavior on the site. Before we begin analyzing the results, we will check to ensure users were allocated equally to the test and control groups.

In [30]:
# compute and plot allocations across marketing channels
alloc_house_ads = allocation('House Ads')
alloc_facebook = allocation('Facebook')
alloc_push = allocation('Push')
alloc_inst = allocation('Instagram')
alloc_email = allocation('Email')

fig, ax = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize=(10, 8), sharex=True)
plot_ads(ax[0, 0], alloc_house_ads, 'bar', 'Allocation House Ads', 'Number of users')
plot_ads(ax[0, 1], alloc_facebook, 'bar', 'Allocation Facebook', 'Number of users')
plot_ads(ax[1, 0], alloc_push, 'bar', 'Allocation Push', 'Number of users')
plot_ads(ax[1, 1], alloc_inst, 'bar', 'Allocation Instagram', 'Number of users')
plot_ads(ax[2, 0], alloc_email, 'bar', 'Allocation Email', 'Number of users')
plt.show()

Allocations for House Ads and Email are relatively even, but not exactly the same. But there are differences in allocations for Push, Facebook and Instagram. We can clearly see more personalization messaging compared with the control for those tree channels. Now, we will compute conversion rates for the control and personalization groups. We will evaluate whether the conversion was higher in the personalization treatment compared with the control.

Overall conversion rates, lift and t-statistics for control and personalization groups¶

Now, we will calculate overall conversion rate for control and personalization groups and lift. Lift means if the conversion rate was higher for the treatment and by how much. Also, we compute t-statistics by performing t-test. T-test allows to find out if the result of A/B test is statistically significant and can be used to make business decisions.

In [31]:
# compute overall conversion rate for control and personalization groups
subscribers_ab = marketing.groupby(['user_id', 'variant'])['converted'].max().unstack(level=1)
control = subscribers_ab['control'].dropna()
personalization = subscribers_ab['personalization'].dropna()
print('Overall control conversion rate:', round(np.mean(control), 4))
print('Overall personalization conversion rate:', round(np.mean(personalization), 4))
print('lift:', lift(control, personalization))
print(ttest_ind(control, personalization))

Overall control conversion rate: 0.099
Overall personalization conversion rate: 0.1691
lift: 70.81%
Ttest_indResult(statistic=-8.873395769885624, pvalue=8.747611948132341e-19)

We can clearly see that personalization converted users at around 71% higher rate than the control. Moreover, p-value is less than 0.05 which means that the result is statistically significant and can be used for developing a marketing strategy.

Conclusion¶

In conclusion, we measured the marketing campaign performance by computing conversion rate and retention rate metrics. Thus, all marketing assets converted around 14% of users and 64% of them remained subscribers. However, conversion rate and retention rate differ in demographics, languages, and marketing channels. Email channel (35%), German (75%) and Arabic (55%) languages and age groups younger than 30 years (17-25%) have the highest conversion rates. Alternatively, Push (6%) and House Ads (6%) channels, Spanish (18%) and English (12%) languages and age groups older than 30 years (around 7%) have the lowest conversion rates. When it comes to retention rate, Push, Instagram, and Facebook channels (around 70% each), German and English languages (62%), and age groups 55+years, 24-30 years, and 19-24years (65%) have the highest retention rates. On the other hand, House Ads (58%) and Email (62%) channels, Spanish (54%) and Arabic (59%) languages and age groups 45-55 years (53%) and 36-45 years (54%) have the lowest retention rates.

Furthermore, two issues were detected while analysis. Firstly, 571 users were marked retained but not converted. Those observations were isolated and sent to the marketing team for clarification. Secondly, after the 11th of January 25 ads or 12% have been displayed in the not correct languages each day. This issue resulted in losing 24 potential subscribers.

According to A/B test analysis, the control messaging converted around 10% of users but the personalized marketing assets converted around 17% of users or higher by 71%. However, conversion rate differs in demographics, marketing channels and languages. We can clearly see a trend indicating that users who are younger than 30 years prefer the personalized messages but users who are older 30 years have been converted better by the control ads. When it comes to marketing channels, all the channels except House Ads shows that the personalization converted users more effectively than the control. The result of A/B test is statistically significant and can be used for making business decisions.
